title: 3rd Ave. and Jefferson St. after the fire, July 1889
Shirley Frazier, March 13, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1459. Shirley Frazer is best riflewoman in U.S. Seattle, Washington. - 100, 100 100, 99, 99, 100 is the way the scorer chalked up this Co-ed's record in the National shoot. Miss Frazer is a University of Washington co-ed and in her recent record she got 598 out of a possible 600, which is only one point removed from an all time record, she tied last year with Mary Wettach of Carnegie Tech and lost the toss of the coin for first place. Direct service...3/13/35...exclusive..."

title: View north from 2nd Ave. and Virginia St., 1882
Seattle from Elliott Bay, ca. 1930
description: The Northern Life Tower can be seen at the left of the photograph. Smith Tower and the Colman Dock appear at the right.

title: Badminton players Keith Weston and Hamilton Law, January 28, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1382. Favorites come through badminton tourney. Seattle, Washington. - The biggest entry list in the state has just finished a week of badminton tournament. With players from all parts of the country, Seattle stars won their way through the finals. Photo shows winners in the men's doubles Keith Weston and Hamilton Law on the courts of Queen Anne Hall. Law also one shuttle contest. Direct service... 1/28/35...exclusive..." The 1935 city directory lists Queen Anne Hall at 713 1st Ave. W.

title: Cornish dance students in Volunteer Park, April 19, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1552. Its springtime in Seattle. Seattle Washington. - The farthest north big metropolis in United States is putting on her fine garments for Easter and with all the spring beauty, comes the fait maiden to dance with joy for the spring. Out in Volunteer Park, on top of the highest knowl [sic] in the city, blossoms are at their best, even calling Cornish School dancers to romp in the warm sunshine and fragrance of the season atmosphere. Photo shows Doreen Lang, of San Francisco, Eve Simeon Seattle and Nina Fonaroff of New York City in their Albanian costumes folk dance in Volunteer Park. Direct service...4/19/1935...exclusive..."
subjects: Cornish School of Allied Arts (Seattle, Wash.)

title: President Garfield Memorial Service at Occidental Hotel, September 26, 1881
Lake Washington Blvd. looking toward Mt. Rainier, ca. 1910
Aurora Kippenberg and Helene Madison at the Alki Marathon, July 29, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1049. Aurora Kippenberg, heroine of Alki Marathon. Seattle, Washington. - Three girls and one man finish the Hi-Yu marathon, that is one of the greatest tests in this part of the country. There were 35 entries, but physical tests forbade all but fifteen in taking the change. Among these where was one man and three girls. Photo shows Miss Aurora Kippenberg being given the grease treatment by Helene Madison Seattle's wonder girl swimmer. Direct service...7/29/34..."

title: William Head, ca. 1890
description: Transcribed from photograph front: "Wm. Head - Aunt Matilda's boy, Oregon."" Transcribed from photograph back: ""William Head, State of Washington, Aunt Matilda's oldest son + child. 19 in the family." The 1885 Washington State Territorial Census lists a Matilda Head residing in King County.

title: Cherry St. in the snow, January 10, 1880
description: Seattle in snow. Cherry Street looking northeast. Store signs: Coulter & Shillestad Undertakers, Spring-Beds.

title: Paul Satko's children being taken into custody by Juvenile Court, April 25, 1940
description: Transcribed from photograph: "562778. Children taken from Alaska-bound ark. Seattle--Despite efforts to hid in the hold of the home-made Ark of Juneau, bound from Tacoma, Wash. to Alaska, five of the minor children of Paul Satko were taken into temporary custody by the Juvenile Court at Seattle. The action came after a court order was served on Satko, ordering him to turn the children over to authorties on grounds that the ark was unsafe. Here the children are shown on their way to court. Hazel, 18, who wasn't held; Joe, 16; David, 9; Billie, 8; and Grace, 11, partly hidden. Credit line (ACME) 4-26-40." The same photograph appeared in the Seattle Times on April 25, 1940.

title: Washington Athletic Club relay team and coach, March 13, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1485. Coach Daughters gives relay last workout before coming to eastern meet. Seattle, Washington. - Coach Ray Daughters gave his wonder girl relay team a fast workout and instructions before he started for an eastern invasion in swimming meets. His relay team will take daily workouts and join their coach in Chicago on April 4th to compete in the women's national indoor meet at Lakeshore. A.C. L to R: Mary Lou Petty, Olive McKean, Betty Lee, Doris Buckley, and Coach Ray Daughters.  Direct service...3/22/35...exclusive..."

title: Seattle Mayor Charles L. Smith, ca., 1935
description: Smith served as Mayor between 1934 and 1936.

title: World's Fair visitors at post office, 1962
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle -- World's Fair visitors head for the Space Needle Station of the Seattle Post Office. The Post Office is next to the Great Britain Exhibit. (World's Fair Photo No. PO 6697mf)."
subjects: United States Post Office (Century 21 Exposition, 1962, Seattle, Wash.)
photographer: Public Relations Department, Seattle World's Fair

title: Crowd cheering returning troops, March 3, 1952
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle-style welcome: Despite the fact that it was Sunday-and a chilly afternoon, hundreds of Seattleites assembled at Third Avenue "Welcome Lane" yesterday to cheer troops who arrived from the Far East aboard the transport Antolak. The ceremony was held between Union and Pike Streets. The convoy of busses took the troops to Fort Lawton. Mar. 3, 1952." Photograph appeared in the Seattle Times.

title: Satko family on grounded "Ark" in Seattle, April 30, 1940
description: Transcribed from photograph: "NY 162--Paul Satko, Richmond welder, his wife and 7 children study plight after ark they started to Alaska on went aground off Seattle."

title: Pioneer Building, ca. 1910
description: The Pioneer Building appears in the center of the photograph with the Howard Building to its left and Hotel Seattle to its right.

title: Paul Satko being served with court order, April 26, 1940
description: Seattle Times, April 27, 1940: Transcribed from photograph: "553779. Owner of Alaska-Bound Ark jailed. Seattle--Paul Satko's pioneering journey from Tacoma, Wash. to Alaska in his homemade Ark of Juneau was interrupted when he was arrested for resisting an officer and five of his seven children were taken into temporary custody of the juvenile court at Seattle. His arrest came after he was served with a court order to turn the children over to authorities on grounds that the ark was unsafe. The previous day the ark had cone aground in Puget Sound. This picture shows the order being served. Satko is in the center wearing overalls. Credit line (ACME) 4-26-40."

title: Henry L. Yesler residence, ca. 1890
description: After Henry Yesler's death, the mansion housed the Seattle Public Library. It was destroyed in a 1901 fire.

title: Barney Ross, national welter weight, meeting with Howard Dent Jr. from University of Washington, April 2, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1508. Barney Ross arrives in Seattle for match with Henry Wood for title. Seattle, Washington. - Barney Ross, National welter weight has arrived in Seattle to defend his title against Henry Wood, the sturdy Washingtonian in a twelve round bout in Seattle's civic auditorium next week. The champion looks good after a few weeks in the hot springs and there is little doubt that he will come out the heavy man on the tales to put Woods away in a hurry. The first man to greet Ross at the Seattle[Washington] Athletic Club Training quarters was Howard Dent, jr. heavy weight wrestler of the University of Washington. Dent is the blind wrestler who has astonished the world wi th his blind skill in the heavies. His weight is 190 pounds and he is just now slated to take on a bout at Multnomah Club of Portland in the P.N.A. of the A.A.U. wrestling tournament. Photo shows Barney Ross wishing good luck to the blind wrestler on his tour of the Northwest. Direct service...4/2/35...exclusive."

title: Art Ahonon and Tom Yelich of the University of Washington football team, September 24, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA 1180: Look what Art Ahonen brought back from Ironwood Michigan. Seattle, Washington. - Art Ahonen big end of University of Washington for the third year has just reported to coach Phelan. The boss needed a center and art brought one for him, all the way form Ironwood, Michigan. He is Tom Yelich at the left in this photograph. Art is telling him to look like Ironwood. Direct service...9/24/34..."

title: View north on 2nd Ave. from Yesler Way, ca. 1923
description: Transcribed from photograph: "The downtown business section, Seattle. Looking north up 2nd Ave, with Elliott Bay and the Olympic Mountains to the west." Photo is likely taken from Smith Tower. The Mehlhorn and Empire buildings appear on the right.

title: University of Washington Shipping Board School, 1918
description: Transcribed from photograph: "U.S. Shipping Board School. U of W. 1918." The Shipping Board School was a free program in Marine Engineering established at the University of Washington by the United States Shipping Board.

title: Yesler home near 1st Ave. and Yesler Way, 1860
description: The same photograph is appears in the Prosch Seattle Views Collection at the University of Washington with the following description: "This is the oldest or first known photograph of any part of Seattle. It represents that part of town from the south line of Cherry Street on the left to the north line of James Street on the right, extending from First to Third Avenues east and west. The buildings shown are the Yesler dwelling in the foreground, and two barns or outbuildings of his. The Hillory Butler Home is back of Yesler's. Opposite the nearest barn is the L.V. Wyckoff house. On its right is the H.A. Smith house. South of James St. is the S.D. Libby house, later that of John Collins. These buildings occupied the ground now covered by immense brick houses, reaching up to sixteen stories in one case. The pole shown stood in front of the Yesler sawmill, where Pioneer Place now is. A V-shaped flume shows in the picture. It brought water down James Street. Seattle's first shade trees, framed in, are seen, or supposed to be seen on the right of the Yesler house. The picture was taken in 1860."

title: Seattle Seahawks hockey team, March 25, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1492: It looks like Seahawks for Championship for Northwest League."" March 25, 1935. Seattle, Washington.- 4,000 hockey fans rattled the rafters of Seattle Ice Arena in a crucial game of the 35 season playoff on Sunday. As it stands the Seattle team has two to one advantage over the Vancouver team and if Seahawks win the next it will be all over. The next game is to be played in Vancouver and if necessary for the fifth game it will be played in Seattle this weekend. L to R. Couch and Manager Frank Foyston, Johnny Houbregs, Moon Mullen, defense, Cameron Proudlock forward, Tony Hemerling, forward, Harold Tabor, forward, Les Whittles, forward, Dave Gilhooly defense and Emmett Venne goalie. Seattle 5, Vancouver 2. Direct service...3/35/35..."

title: Boxing match between Barney Ross and Henry Wood, April 10, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1528. Barney Ross wins decision over Henry Wood in 12 round battle. Seattle, Washington. - When Henry Wood ran into a haymaker. Photo shows left Henry Wood welter weight running into one of Barney Ross's left hooks to the face. New York and Chicago. 4/10/35." According to Seattle Times articles from April 10, the match took place in the Civic Auditorium.

title: Civic Auditorium and Mount Rainier, ca. 1950
description: Photograph taken looking south from lower Queen Anne. The Civic Auditorium and Armory appear on the lower right and Mount Rainier appears in the center.

title: Fire at Brace Lumber Company, May 10, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1588. Strike pickets blamed for hampering firemen at Seattle midnight fire. Seattle, Washington. - With the lumber industry tied up on account labor troubles, it is believed that the $15,000 fire that swept the Brace Lumber Company in ruins and threatened destruction to a big brewery and an oil and gas storage company in the same block, that striking pickets did hamper the work of the fire department of Seattle last night at midnight. Photo shows the raging fire within a few feet of the big brewery. Direct service...5/10/1935..." The 1935 city directory lists the Brace Lumber Company at 925 Valley St.

title: Harry Givan plays for a place in the National Open, May 14, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1612. Northwest all set for two siege guns for National Open. Seattle, Washington. - Harry Givan, ""Amateur"" of Seattle shot a 142 for an [illegible] test to place in the National Open in Pittsburgh June 6,7, and 8th. His 142 was four strokes above par for the 36 holes. Direct service...5/15/35...exclusive..." A May 14, 1935 Seattle Times article identifies the location of the competition at the Seattle Golf Club.

title: View SE from 4th Ave. and Seneca St., 1887
description: Providence Hospital appears in the center of the photograph and the Central School appears above it to the left.

title: Waterfront between Madison and Columbia St., 1887
description: Seattle waterfront between Columbia and Madison Street. YMCA, Budlong's boathouse, and Golden Rule Bazaar.

title: Queen Coffee and Waffle House interior, ca. 1910
description: A 1910 Seattle Times article lists the Waffle House at 119 1/2 W. Main St. This refers to the area west of 1st Ave. that is now called S. Main St. The 119 location corresponds roughly with the present day address of 81 S. Main St.
subjects: Queen Coffee and Waffle House (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Group of boys, ca. 1925
description: Location and identities of the boys unknown.

title: Paul and Hazel Satko with lawyers, April 27, 1940
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Friends come to aid of Paul Satko, unemployed welder, at Seattle April 25, after his Alaska trip in a home-made Ark was halted by legal complaints the craft was unsafe. He's shown here conferring outside juvenile court, which took custody of his children. Left to right, Lee Merrill, Tacoma, Wash., supporter; Hazel Satko, 18; Satko; and attorneys Horace Geer and Milton Heiman." The same photograph appeared in the Seattle Times on April 25, 1940.

title: Baron Walter von Pachman of Bavaria, February 27, 1929
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SF Bureau--Cleve--NY ACME--Airmail--Feb 27, 1929. He was Baron Walter von Pachman of Bavaria, son of a high German army officer and himself somewhat scarred in university duels. Now, he's a bus boy at Seattle Hotel, and his wife is a waitress in the coffee shop of the same hostelry. The pair are out of employment after the subdivision of a large ranch where he was agricultural expert, and between carrying trays, the Baron is looking for employment as a chemist."

title: Tod Markow, UW football player, September 24, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA. 1179. Whats the mystery about Huskies? Seattle, Washington. - People don't think much of the Washington Huskies changes this year. "Too many graduates last spring" Coach Jimmie Phelan, but every time you size up a likely candidate and ask where he comes from. O! That guy comes from Chicago, or Michigan, or somewhere other than Washington where they raise tall timber. Tod Markow the tall end this year comes from Chicago and if Jimmie does not keep him under a blanket the early part of the season, he is just likely enough to start something. Direct service...9/24/34...exclusive..."

title: Bob Swisher practicing high jump, March 22, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Husky jumpers trying out artificial lighting of indoors prepatory [sic] to Stanford meet. Seattle, Washington. - Bob Swisher, crack high jumper of the Washington Huskies is expected to give Stanford a hard run for first place in their meet at University of Washington Pavilion March 29 when the two teams meet for the first competitive event of the season for the Huskies. Heck Edmondson is still trying out his jumpers by strong lighting floods for the big event. Direct service...3/22/35...exclusive..."

title: Roosevelt Theater, 1953
description: The Roosevelt Theater was first opened in 1933. The name of theater was changed to the Town Theater in 1964.

title: Elsie Morrison, UW archer, December 24, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1#27. Archery Becoming Popular at University of Washington. Seattle, Washington. - Miss Elsie Morrison of the University of Washington shows how the co-eds keep fit these winter days when one cannot enjoy outdoor sports. It takes considerable strength to pull the big bow and developes the whole upper structure of the body. There are 24 different kinds of sports taught in the physical education department of U of Washington. Direct and section #3...12/24/34..."

title: Mayor Edwin A. Brown and bull, February 11, 1926
description: Transcribed from photograph: "20770. You may think this is a lot of bull. A real, honest-to-goodness bull strolled into the office of Mayor Edwin Brown, of Seattle, Wash., the other day. The mayor granted the bull the privilege of an executive conference, but refused to divulge the details."

title: George Eddy, inventor of the golf fairway vacuum cleaner, November 16, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1266. Three cheers for inventor of golf fairway vacuum cleaner. Seattle, Washington. - George Eddy, owner of Foster Golf Course, has solved the question of the Autumn, when the leaves are falling and you know that your ball is straight down the fairway, but still cannot find it on account of leaves on the course. "Well just call George and he will do it." Edwards has invented a vacuum cleaner for the golf links and it works, no matter what the conditions, George will guarantee a clean course. The cleaner is not unlike then ordinary household vacuum cleaner, in principal, but hitched to a tractor it runs over the course and takes every fallen leaf. Direct service...11/16/34...exclusive..."

title: View east from 4th Ave. S. and S. Jackson St., June 1920
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Book page 224. Historic railway terminal (at right). Seattle, Wash. Photo by H.H. Waller. June 1920." Union Station appears to the right. Hotel Idaho is visible in the center of the photograph.

title: 3rd Ave. and Jefferson St. after the fire, July 1889
Collapsed East Gate at World Fair grounds, February 26, 1962
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Builders' Work is Un-Fair. What goes up must come down. But workmen erecting the facilities for the Seattle World's Fair are not pleased that their work is undone before the exposition opens. A 40-foot-high laminated wooden arch at the main east entryway collapsed into a heap of splinters Monday. Construction foreman Del Yount said he thought a gust of wind did the damage. The Men were standing under the arch but escaped without injury."

title: Bertha Barkhoff and Zoe Smith, badminton finalists, April 1, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1507. Badminton stars come through according to form. Mrs. Bert Barkhoff [Bertha] and Zoe Smith of Seattle won their place in the State finals at Badminton at Queen Anne Hall last night. After a tour of the Pacific Coast this team came right back and showed the homefolk that their awards were of the first water. They won their set be a score of 15-11 to 15-8. Photo shows Mrs. Barkhoff shooting a back-hand with Miss Zoe Smith backing up. Direct service...4/1/35...exclusive..."

title: A.J. Heller and Earl Martin outside of Labor Temple, July 16, 1919
Bertha Barkhoff, badminton champion, April 1, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1506. Seattle, Washington. - Mrs. Bert [Bertha] Barkhoff took a few lessons recently from the great National Champion, Jess Willard, and then went right out and beat the best they had to offer in Portland, Oregon, then to San Francisco she won the women's championship and on the Los Angeles she still was the best in the singles and now she is back on her home courts and last night she captured the singles and paired with Miss Zoe Smith took the women's doubles. Photo shows Mrs. Bert Barkhoff with one of her easy back-hand sweeps that is deadly to her opponent. Direct service...4/1/35...exclusive..."

title: Bob Snyder of Butterfly Bob's Salad Bar, October 8, 1974
description: Transcribed from photograph: "ARP 092703--UNIPIX. Winged Delivery. Seattle, Wash: - Bob Snyder, co-owner of Butterfly Bob's Salad Bar here, hopes this outfit will attract attention to his business -- especially when he begins delivery service in the downtown area shortly. Bob says his wings will have big pockets to carry sandwiches, and he promises delivery with a half-hour of the order within a two-block radius of his restaurant. Credit (UPI). 10/8/74."

title: University of Washington vs. Idaho football game, September 19, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1185. Washington Huskies beat Idaho 13 to 0. Seattle, Washington. - Burl Bufkin nailed by of [sic] Idaho in an attempt to run the end was a clever bit of tackling for the Vandals. The Vandals held the Huskies for the first half and it was in the third quarter that Phelans mob got going. Direct service...9/29/34..."
